==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mis-
<hw>Mis-</hw> <pr>(m⟦icr⟧s-)</pr>. <ety>[In words of Teutonic origin,
fr. AS. <ets>mis-</ets>; akin to D. <ets>mis-</ets>, G.
<ets>miss-</ets>, OHG. <ets>missa-</ets>, <ets>missi-</ets>, Icel. &
Dan. <ets>mis-</ets>, Sw. <ets>miss-</ets>, Goth. <ets>missa-</ets>;
orig., a p. p. from the root of G. <ets>meiden</ets> to shun, OHG.
<ets>m⟦imac⟧dan</ets>, AS. <ets>m⟦imac⟧⟦edh⟧an</ets> (⟦root⟧100. Cf.
<er>Miss</er> to fail of). In words from the French, fr. OF.
<ets>mes-</ets>, F. <ets>m⟦eacute⟧-</ets>, <ets>mes-</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>minus</ets> less (see <er>Minus</er>). In present usage these two
prefixes are commonly confounded.]</ety> <def>A prefix used adjectively
and adverbially in the sense of <sig>amiss</sig>, <sig>wrong</sig>,
<sig>ill</sig>, <sig>wrongly</sig>, <sig>unsuitably</sig>; <as>as,
<ex>mis</ex>deed, <ex>mis</ex>lead, <ex>mis</ex>chief,
<ex>mis</ex>creant</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mis</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mis
<hw>Mis</hw> <pr>(m⟦icr⟧s)</pr>, <pos>a. & adv.</pos> <ety>[See
<er>Amiss</er>.]</ety> <def>Wrong; amiss.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
⟦ldquo⟧To correcten that [which] is <xex>mis</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Misacceptation</ent>⟦br⟧
